Starting with a base rate of zero. This has never happened before. Trading has stopped a few times in the past, such as 09/11/2001 attacks, and a technical glitch in 2013, as others have pointed out. Current Crowd Forecast is 1% chance, will use as my initial probability. Attribution to a cyberattack is also difficult. Attack would have to be acknowledged, and made public. Attack may or may not be attributed to a specific country, group, or source. Attribution to a country has huge political implications. Non-attribution to a source gives appearance of incompetence. Even if NYSE is attacked and shutdown, this could be hidden. It could be attributed to glitch or error, and not an attack. Current financial and geopolitical instability from COVID-19 makes things more tense, slightly increases chances for attack.

China and Russia have both infiltrated out electrical grids, so I think it is safe to assume they have infiltrated stock market systems as well. I think there is a decent chance they will mess with that system in the coming months to sow chaos and confusion, attempt to interfere with the us election, or divert us attention away from their attempts to consolidate power elsewhere.

A cyberwar with Iran is highly possible. Iran may have fewer restraints than other American adversaries like Russia, North Korea, or China, leading to attacks that are both “aggressive and unpredictable - to the point of being reckless.” Tehran is likely to lean on its proxy forces, including Hezbollah and Hamas, to effectively launch a full-scale attack. Critical infrastructures like power grids and the financial system have long been seen as ripe targets for cyber warfare, but Iran may look to the Russian playbook, to focus any offensive campaign on President Trump himself, conducting influence operations including meddling in the upcoming U.S. Presidential election. The U.S. government has increased cyber capabilities dramatically over the years, Defense Department’s tools against any attack are unmatched, but the U.S. remains vulnerable in part because it doesn’t impose the kind of control Iran does over the internet. BUT: To halt the NYSE from now to August 2020 seems unlikely, also considering that the damage inflicted on a Cyberattack to NYSE may be limited and it will be very unlikely that NYSE will make it public before this date. I researched a bit on the subject in question before making the forecast, keeping it to the high limit of 1% in the current context. If I could, I would place it somewhere around or below 0.5%.
There seem to be a lot of increasing estimates due to the Iran issue.
Iran is said to have the ability to launch a cyber attack the NYSE, and they are now looking for a way to attack the US.
It certainly would be an attractive option for Iran to do something like halt trading.

Increasing by 7% given that it is very likely that retaliation from Iran for the United States' killing of its top general will, at least in part, consist of cyber attacks [1,2,3]. Indeed, Iran has already targeted the NYSE in 2012 - however, this took the form of a relatively unsophisticated DDOS attack [4]. If such an attack were to occur again, it seems very unlikely it would result in a cross-market trading halt. But Iran does seem to have significantly strengthened its cyber capabilities [5] since then, so by now they might be capable of more powerful attacks - though I still think a cross-market trading halt would be unlikely because A) they still might not be capable of it and B) it is overwhelmingly likely that retaliatory Iranian cyber attack(s) will instead strike at other targets.
Such an event is extremely unlikely, because even those who might be able to to it (only very few are), have nothing to gain from it.

Cyber attacks are becoming more and more common and per Forbes financial institutions are high frequency targets. However, who would launch a cyber attack against the NYSE? It would require someone with an awful lot of sophistication, either a government or a very knowledgeable organized computer crime group. A solo hacker (someone weighing 400 lbs sitting on his bed) is unlikely. Which foreign governments would want to cyber attack? The obvious ones are North Korea, Russia and Iran. There might be a few others, but I can't think of them right now. North Korea would be by far the most likely. They cyber hacked Sony when they did not like a movie so they probably have the ability but why would they? Why do they launch missiles and develop nuclear weapons? I suspect because they want to be a player on the world stage without entering into a self-destructive war. A cyber attack would do just that. Russian likely would not do such a thing as long as their favorite president was in the White House and afterward probably would not want the resulting post-attack sanctions. Next, Iran would. They attacked Saudi Arabia recently with drones. Iran hates us, but they probably do not have the ability and would likely attack a greater Satan first, e.g., Saudi Arabia or Kuwait.

NYSE has never in its history attributed a cross-market trading halt to a cyber attack so this would be a highly unprecedented event. The only cross-market trading halt driven by operational issues in recent years was in 2015, suggesting that these types of events are very unusual. On average 1 major US financial services firm per year attributes operational disruption to cyber attacks again suggesting the chances that NYSE makes this attribution is low. Nonetheless, NYSE is likely to be a prime target for certain threat actors which could suggest a less than negligible chance of this event happening.
Even if it does occur, NYSE is unlikely to publicly acknowledge this without obfuscating the truth. Acknowledging that it has been successfully cyberattacked will be bad for business.

Protecting the election from cyber attacks will be priorities 1-10 for cyber crime fighters and that could lead to opportunities in other areas. As FBI agent Fitzhugh told McNulty, "after 911 the Bureau doesn't care about drugs unless they are tied to terrorism."

Some of the best security on the planet will continue to be in place at the NYSE and only an extraordinary event will beat it.

Base rate: It seems like trading on the NYSE has never come to a halt as a result of a cyberattack. There have been a few times when technical glitches [1] or geopolitical events [2] brought trading to a halt, but these were not related to cyberattacks. There have, however, been smaller-scale cyber attacks on stock exchanges across the globe, with one report finding that about half of exchanges were the target of cyber attacks in a given year [3].
